,Not Recommended,324190,19413777,"Posted: 1 December, 2015",all,ds6,"NOTE: This review was made for an earlier version of the game and I haven't kept up on the progress of it, so this review may be outdated in terms of current game content.I don't really understand why the game is getting the reviews it is. I understand it's early access, but there are a lot of things that should have been done from the get-go from a design perspective.  Here is a list of problems I have with it.- One of the first things I noticed is that there's no infinite loop checking, and you can easily lock up you game by making one. Well, at least with JS, and on that note it could just be a JS issue that Blockly detects but I honestly can't be arsed to check. That not being implemented (for the JS, at least) really shows what kind of game these guys are making, one focused on final results rather than code implementation. For me, this is a big red flag, even though it might seem trivial or nothing at all to someone else. If it is in this state because it was released too early, thendon't release it until it's ready for players to test. I am entirely certain that some prodigious beginner programmer has at one point crafted a beautiful spell just to have it be destroyed with a game-freezing accidental open loop that they can't fix.- Even if one does get far enough into the game as to be able to freeze it like that, the UI feels... unresponsive. I found it difficult to find specific functions In the Blockly editor, and what little time I spent with the interface felt unintuitive and haphazard. Orb creation isn't even called that, rather it's listed as casting another spell... While this makes sense logically based on how the game works (one orb per spell), my first instict was to look for ""Create orb"" or similar. Even Multimedia Fusion does it better.- The JS editor is okay, and has a number of simplistic IDE-like features, such as syntax highlighting, simplistic realtime syntax and error checking, and the occasional autocomplete, but the clunkyness and unresponsiveness of the UI still really hampered the experience. Also I wasn't able to find any select all option, to copy it into something that didn't suck to edit, and the mouse selection works when it wants to. To boot, there was no proper error console for all I could find; errors would just pop up at the bottom of the screen, with a surprising lack of information related to the error. Having an actual console likenearly every other programmable gamewould be nice, guys.- There is a code converter that converts Blockly code blocks into JS... This leads me to believe the code blocks actually just generate JS on the fly, which makes me wonder why you can't do the reverse (i.e. JS to Blockly). You also can't edit the generated JS without making a new spell and copy-pasting it. There isn't even a button to do this on the code generation pane, so you'd have to repeat that process for every spell you want to add a little JS flair to.- There is a distinct lack of proper low-level documentation. Sure, there are some help prompts [in the Blockly interface] and plenty of explanatory beginner spells [also mostly in the Blockly interface], but all of that is just as haphazard as the rest of it. There is no documentation for a number of JS functions that, according to numerous spells posted on their forums, a number of people use regularly. There is no one central place to read about how these functions work, and one of the functions relies on understanding of the underlying Unity framework (it evaluates UnityScript) and how the CodeSpells world is set up programmatically (you can access the game scene from the US scape, which isn't that super unsafe???). At least if you don't want to use those functionalities, there's not a ton of different things to learn and the beginner spells keep it relatively simple, so a new player won't feel overwhelmed...? I guess??- Mana (right? that's what it's called? I forgot already) drain doesn't really make much sense, and there's absolutely zero feedback on what takes what mana and by how much. You can't mix together mana usage very well, either; too little of whatever primary source your spell is assigned to, and it just flat out won't work. You can't change the type of a spell without -- again -- copy-pasting it into a new spell. Nothing but clunk. Maybe this was meant to introduce some challenge and mystique into the game, some guesswork on what will work and what won't. However, code doesn't work like that and will either yell at you or crash silently if you do something wrong. I doubt the game will hold your hand when you try to make this awesome spell to find that it takes way more mana than you even have available to you, and it hurts more knowing that it could have helped you out earlier, saying ""hey this costs 100 so don't use it more than twice"", but that doesn't happen.I really rarely used the Blockly interface, so excuse me if this is actually implemented and I just didn't see it because I only used the Blockly interface to get an idea of what kind of functions there were. That's not an excuse for it not being implemented in the JS portion, however.Aside from the programming, I also have gripes with the presentation of the game:- The game world is incredibly tiny. The edges of the world fall into what appears to be an endless void, and there's no indication other than falling to your untimely death that anything is wrong. I thought it was just a cliff for a moment, and was prepared to create some water with a spell to cushion the landing. That landing never came, as I was just teleported back up to a random position on the map.- While the fluid simulation isverynice, it's incredibly jagged, and really needs some visual polish.- Heating things up doesn't really make as much sense as I'd have expected. Instead of being able to light individual objects on fire, you instead increase the heat of the surrounding area until it gets hot enough for things to burn. Maybe I missed something, but that seems really silly (though having both abilities available would make for smashingly good design). Heating water to create clouds and humidity to create rain (if I was reading that right and it wasn't just random luck) was really awesome, though.TL;DR it has promise, but generally falls flat due to clunky, disjointed interfaces and lack of proper documentation. It tries to be simple and easy to understand, but complicates this by not having a very solid foundation to build on. I certainly wouldn't want anyone to try to learn programming using this tool, especially not my children or anyone I care about.I won't be requesting a refund or anything like that, mostly because I never have and don't want to go through the effort, but I doubt I will be playing this again until these issues are addressed. Yes yes early access blah blah, but not making sure your core gameplay mechanics are fully functional (or at least better alert your buyer that they are still undergoing development) is a downvote from me. The currently implemented features and functionality are done so poorly and there's no excuse for that. Regardless of my personal feelings on the matter, it's certainly not worth its hefty pricetag. Not yet, at least.somewhat related, why teach programming through visual methods like this, and then when they want to get into more serious, low-level stuff, they basically have to relearn everything? why not start with the text but with visual aids? that's just my hatred of visual programming though"
